extracted_content.main_title: Understanding White Oak for Kitchen Cabinets
paragraphs: White oak is not to be confused with rift oak, a technique of cutting wood; it is a different kind than the well-known warm-hued honey-oak (red oak). (You can cut rift both from red and white oak.) See this page to help you decide which of oak and rift-sawn white oak cabinets best suits you.
The wood's appearance and composition differ in several important ways. White wood has a somewhat straight grain pattern; red oak has a curved one.

The Wood Database offers a detailed comparison of red and white oak: "Upon casual observation, raw oak timber usually appears light brown, exhibiting a mild reddish hue (often red oak) or a delicate olive tint (white oak)."
For many reasons, white oak cabinets have delighted homeowners and designers.

extracted_content.main_title: Benefits of White Oak Kitchen Cabinets
paragraphs: When you picture oak cabinets, you probably picture the rich colors popular in the 1980s. Particularly honey wood became rather famous during this era; so much so that many of the best kitchens of the day were overflowing with it. There is great potential in oak that was just disregarded, even if it could be excessive and nothing is more off-putting than a kitchen that looks exactly like all others. Many early 2000s homeowners totally switched to a different type of wood instead of changing oak kitchen designs.

Red oak has become less popular, but oak in general shouldn’t be discounted in the field of interior design. Making a few small changes will help it to recover its prior kitchen excellence—but in a more flexible, aesthetically beautiful manner that will help it to remain fashionable as trends change once more. The fresh, contemporary look of white wood can start this transformation.
There are many benefits to this increasingly chosen alternative. We have found several main advantages from using white oak here:

White oak, with a 1360 hardness value, is sturdier than many other hardwood species. This makes it a perfect choice for often used kitchens since many types of cabinets could soon show dents or scratches. White wood cabinets remain quite beautiful even if they are quite robust.

Usually flat-sawed, the grain patterns associated with ancient oaks were Typical massive cathedral grain patterns connected with oak are produced by a more reasonably priced, high-yielding cut, flat cut.

These days, cabinet artists and quality furniture makers are looking for fresh ideas. Board look from cathedral patterns to straight grains is changed by quarter sawn and rift cut milling. Also adding interesting bits of cross ring development to the look is quarter sawn.

paragraphs: Honey’s and red oak’s warm crimson tones simply aren’t hip these days. We’re not sure if they’ll ever come back, but for the moment this look is best for historical settings. On the other hand, the green-brown tones of white oak with wheat tones present a somewhat contrasting backdrop that fits more with the modern emphasis on neutrals. When building using flooring, counters, and tiles, the softer white oak tones are more suited for generating contrast. White wood provides a subdued foundation for surprising highlights if you’re ready to give your kitchen a little color.

White oak finds application in many different spheres. In modern kitchens, where it can replace white-painted cabinets, adding a little of warmth and character, its modern look is very appealing. To organically beautiful a kitchen, pair white oak cabinets with a dramatic backsplash or a unique island. Moreover, different stains can help to give white oak kitchen cabinets a customized look. We value how stains show the complexity and natural beauty of wood grain.

paragraphs: As said before, usage of red oak in former kitchens is the main reason behind most of today’s uncertainty about oak. White oak’s subdued look can help avoid this problem, but as important is adding contrast to accentuate the depth of your kitchen.

One can reach this with a range of details. Because of its wide spectrum of colors and patterns as well as different textures that would accentuate the wood and draw attention to particular design elements you wish to highlight, backsplash is a perfect choice. One great place to play about with contrast is a countertop. Choose white marble or quartz counters for a polished, sophisticated look; if you want a darker tone, think about dark gray or black counters. White oak’s wood pattern fits the stone’s variance, therefore harmonizing the kitchen.

Additional items that could greatly affect the whole impact are flooring, fixtures, and hardware. To provide more depth and interest, think of combining brushed or matte brass knobs with white oak or choosing a highly polished finish. kitchens including two-tone designs can also feature white oak. Don’t hesitate to boldly highlight the best features of white oak.
